.content-parent
  .content-area-1
    %h3 Design Principles
    %h3 Most content will go in it's own content box.
    %h4 This box has a mid-grey outline and a slightly heavier top border.
    %p This means all questions relating to solar go in one content box.
    %p All questions relating to batteries go in another content box.
    %p Any questions relating to hydro go in another content box.
    %p Any questions relating to wind go in another content box.
    %p Given the -pre-approval tool is a form, users will respond well to it being vertically aligned and of a fixed width, centrally on the page.
    %p As such, a content width of 500px is used for all content areas, with width reducing for mobile.
    %p As much as is possible, inputs and buttons should fill the width of the container, with 30px padding either side.
    %p There are some exceptions, such as the "plus" button, which is smaller as an affordance to clicking.
    %h3 Buttons
    %p Buttons should go in the box relating to the action they are associated with.
    %a.button{:href=>"/styleguide"}
      This is a primary content-level button
    %a.button.secondary{:href=>"/styleguide"}
      This is a secondary content-level button
    %a.button.tertiary{:href=>"/styleguide"}
      This is an tertiary content-level button


  .button-area-1
    %p Page-level buttons, such as "Next" and "Go Back" should live in their own box.
    %a.button{:href=>"/styleguide"}
      This is a page-level button
    %a.button.tertiary{:href=>"/styleguide"}
      This enables a user to go back

.content-parent
  .content-area-1
    %h1 Page and background
    %p The entire page should nestle within the existing header and footer of the AusNet Services website.
    %p With the exception of the red and green boxes all content should be on a white background.
    %p Behind all this, there should be the stacking cube motif as seen on the AusNet Services website.

.content-parent
  .content-area-1
    %h1 Sample Page Layout
    %p Below is a sample page layout, including several separated content areas, and a separate area for buttons.
    %br
    %h2 First up, there's a starter question
    = render "layouts/yes-or-no"
    %br
    %h2 Then there's some questions based on that answer
    %p If a user answers "no" above, then all of the inputs related to that "yes / no" in the box should disappear.
    %p In most cases, users will be detailing the inverter setup for their proposed system.
    .text-input
      %form
        %label This is a multiple choice dropdown
        %select{:class=>"multipleChoice"}
          %option{:value=>"1"} Option 1
          %option{:value=>"2"} Option 2
          %option{:value=>"3"} Option 3
        %label This is a free text field
        %input
      %form.quantity
        %div
          %label Quantity
          %input
        .remove-inverter
          .button.secondary remove this inverter
    %h3 Users should be given the opportunity to add more inverters, or remove them if they make a mistake.
    .add-inverter
      %h3 add an inverter...
      %p This section expands when a user clicks the "plus" button, and it duplicates the inputs above.
      %a.plus-button{:type=>"checkbox", :id=>"monthly", :name=>"switch", :checked=>"checked", :class=>"inverterToggler1"}
        .plus +
    %br

  .content-area-1
    %h2 This is another content area
    %p If the user has already filled in information about their solar inverters, we might use this section to ask them about their battery inverters.
    %br
    %h3 Is your system configuration AC or DC coupled?
    .ac-dc-toggle
      .ac.toggle-active AC
      .dc DC
    .text-input
      %form
        %label This is a multiple choice dropdown
        %select{:class=>"multipleChoice"}
          %option{:value=>"1"} Option 1
          %option{:value=>"2"} Option 2
          %option{:value=>"3"} Option 3
        %label This is a free text field
        %input
      %form.quantity
        %div
          %label Quantity
          %input
        .remove-inverter
          .button.secondary remove this inverter
  .button-area-1
    %h2 Finally, we can have page-level actions
    %p these can happen once a user has entered all their data.
    %a.button{:href=>"/styleguide"}
      Next
    %a.button.tertiary{:href=>"/styleguide"}
      Go back

.content-parent#dynamicWarning
  .content-area-1.instructionContent
    %h3 This is a dynamic warning that appears when a user takes an action that means they can't proceed, such as adding too many inverters.
    %p You can add a button to dismiss it.
    %p In the case of a user adding too many inverters, there souldn't be a button, rather the dynamic warning should disappear when they make a change to their inverters.
    .button.secondary.dismissDynamic
      Dismiss